ry, with the South-Central Ridge of the Delhi Ridge encompassing the area and this forest is called [[Sanjay Van]]. The other residential areas in proximity are Chattarpur, Saket, Malviya Nagar, Mahipalpur, Lado Sarai, Ber Sarai and Neb Sarai. The residential part of Vasant Kunj is divided into 5 Sectors - A, B, C, D and E.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delhiinformation.in/delhi/areas/vasant-kunj.html|title=Vasant Kunj|accessdate=13 February 2018}}</ref> Each Sector is further divided into Pockets.\n\n==In History==\n[[Sultan Ghari]]'s tomb in Vasant Kunj is considered as the first Islamic [[mausoleum]] in Delhi. The historic [[Qutb Minar]] complex is located close to Vasant Kunj.\n\n==Economy==\n[[Bloomsbury India]] has its head office in the Vishrut Building (Building No. 3) in the DDA Complex in Vasant Kunj. Also the corporate offices of the [[Bharti Enterprises]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airtel.in/about-bharti/equity/support-and-communication/|title=Investor Support - Shareholders Communication - airtel|website=www.airtel.in|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> [[Maruti Suzuki|Maruti Suzuki India Ltd.]] and [[Oil and Natural Gas Corporation]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionweekonline.in/cccl-to-build-ongc-corporate-office/|title=CCCL to build ONGC corporate office|website=constructionweekonline.in|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> are located in the area near Ambience mall.<ref>\"[http://www.bloomsbury.com/uk/company/contact-us/ Contact Us].\" [[Bloomsbury Books]]. Retrieved on 14 October 2012. \"Bloomsbury India Bloomsbury Publishing India Pvt Limited VISHRUT Building Building no3, DDA Complex, Ground Floor Pocket C 6&7, Vasant Kunj New Delhi 110070 India\"</ref> [[IBM Research|Research Center]] of American multi-national [[IBM]] is located at ISID Campus in Vasant Kunj.<ref>http://www.research.ibm.com/labs/india/visitor-new-delhi.shtml</ref>\n\nDLF's Ambience, [[DLF Promenade|Promenade]] and [[DLF Emporio|Emporio]]<ref>http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2007-11-16/news/27681607_1_global-brands-luxury-mall-dlf-mall</ref> located in Vasant Kunj has been touted as a fashion destination. Vasant Square Mall in Vasant Kunj houses many showrooms<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/autos/triumph-opens-showroom-in-delhi/story-I3XOEokZn5ohFtiJtVeJdL.html|title=Triumph opens showroom in Delhi|date=6 June 2014|website=hindustantimes.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> including one of British bike marker [[Triumph Motorcycles Ltd|Triumph]], BigBazar, KFC and SubWay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.team-bhp.com/news/triumph-inaugurates-showroom-new-delhi-1st-north-india|title=Triumph inaugurates showroom in New Delhi, 1st in North India - Team-BHP|website=team-bhp.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[The Grand New Delhi|The Grand]], a five-star luxury hotel, is located on Nelson Mandela Marg, Vasant Kunj.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegrandnewdelhi.com/contact-us/contact-us.html|title=The Grand New Delhi - 5-Star Luxury Hotel in New Delhi|website=www.thegrandnewdelhi.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>  Export Promotion Council for Handicrafts (E.P.C.H.) is located at Sector C in Vasant Kunj.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epch.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=85&Itemid=173|title=EPCH House Number, Head Office Number, contact Details|website=epch.in|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nVasant Kunj has the country's first community yellow pages since October 1991, called the \"Vasant Kunj Informer & Shopper,\" that has been reaching its booming population month after month, free-of-cost, with user-friendly information of professional services and entrepreneurial work that enhances the quality of the everyday lives of its readers. This community publication continues to touch the lives of thousands of advertisers and readers, especially the student community, in many ways and has added to the vibrancy of its economy.\n\n==Education==\n[[TERI University]] is located in Vasant Kunj.<ref>http://www.teriuniversity.ac.in/#</ref> The new integrated, spacious campus of [[School of Planning and Architecture, Delhi|School of Panning and Architecture]] is undergoing construction off Nelson Mandela Marg. [[Jawaharlal Nehru University, Delhi|Jawarlal Nehru University]] (J.N.U.) including IIMC (Indian Institute of Mass Communications) is surrounded by Vasant Kunj on its west and south. They also have management school Jagannath International Management School.\nShaurya [[Central Reserve Police Force|CRPF]] Officers Training institute is also located in the Vasant Kunj's institutional area near sector C.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.co.in/webhp?sourceid=chrome-instant&rlz=1C1JZAP_enIN679IN679&ion=1&espv=2&ie=UTF-8#q=crpf+shaurya|title=Google|website=www.google.co.in|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nSome of the prominent schools in the neighbourhood includes [[Delhi Public School, Vasant Kunj|Delhi Public School- Vasant Kunj]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-sports/DPS-Vasantkunj-champion/article16817654.ece|title=DPS Vasantkunj champion|date=1 December 2009|publisher=|accessdate=22 January 2018|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> [[Vasant Valley School]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/top-ten-schools-of-south-west-delhi/story-Oe3d0QYlH3S9qTLSrkqoxN.html|title=Top Ten schools of South-West Delhi|date=7 September 2012|website=hindustantimes.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> [[G D Goenka Public School|G.D. Goenka Public School]], [[D.A.V public school]] [[Bhatnagar International School]], [[Ryan International Group of Institutions|Ryan International School]], [[The Heritage School, Delhi|The Heritage School]], [[Bloom Public School]], [https://www.deeppublicschool.co.in Deep Public School] , D-2, Vasant Kunj ,ND,DL,IN=110070.\n\nSome of the playschools and nursery schools are [[Tender Feet Nursery School]], [[Aadyant Global School]], [[Steady Steps International Preschool]].\n\n==Sports==\nVasant Kunj Sports Complex<ref>https://www.dda.org.in/sports/vasant_kunj_sports_complex.htm</ref> is one of the prominent sports complexes developed by Delhi Development Authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ddasports.in/VasantKunj/|title=Vasant Kunj Sports Complex|website=ddasports.in|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> Beeya's Riding Facility in Vasant Kunj is a nationally recognized horse riding club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/check-out-the-horse-riding-schools-in-delhi/1/192490.html|title=Check out the horse-riding schools in Delhi|date=12 December 2005|website=India Today|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Health care==\nIndian Spinal Injuries Centre,<ref>http://www.ilbs.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=101&Itemid=125</ref> Institute of Liver and Biliary Sciences, [[Fortis Healthcare|Fortis]] Flt. Lt. Rajan Dhall Hospital<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fortishealthcare.com/india/hospitals-in-delhi-ncr/fortis-flt-lt-rajan-dhall-hospital-vasant-kunj|title=Top Hospital - Fortis Flt Lt Rajan Dhall Hospital Vasant Kunj Delhi, India|website=Fortis Healthcare Limited|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> are some of the prominent hospitals located in Vasant Kunj. Others include New Delhi Children's Hospital & Research Centre (NDCHRC).\n\n==Government offices==\n[[Central Reserve Police Force]]'s Officers training institute- Shaurya, [[Pension Fund Regulatory and Development Authority]],<ref>http://pfrda.org.in/MyAuth/Admin/showimg.cshtml?ID=520</ref> [[National Book Trust]],<ref>http://www.nbtindia.gov.in/default.aspx</ref> International Centre for Alternate Dispute Resolution<ref>{{cite web|url=http://icadr.nic.in/index.php?page=contact-us&m=31|title=ICADR::Contact Us|website=icadr.nic.in|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref> are located in Vasant Kunj Institutional Area.Indian Aviation Academy\n\n==Getting there==\n[[Indira Gandhi International Airport]] (Terminal 3) is at a distance of 5.9&nbsp;km, while the Domestic Airport (Terminal 1) is at a distance of 7.8&nbsp;km. Nizamuddin Railway Station is 17.8&nbsp; km away while New Delhi Railway Station is at a distance of 18.1&nbsp; km.\n\nThe locality is connected to other regions of New Delhi by road and by [[Delhi Metro|Metro]] rail. Vasant Kunj is accessible by means of public transport including autos, taxis and buses. The nearest Metro stations are [[Chhatarpur metro station|Chattarpur]] on [[Yellow Line (Delhi Metro)|Yellow Line]] , Delhi Aerocity [[Delhi Airport Metro Express|Airport Express(Orange Line)]] and Vasant Vihar(Magenta Line). People who are commuting via [[National Highway 8 (India, old numbering)|NH-8]] can reach Vasant Kunj by taking exit number 2. A new road- Mahipalpur Bypass has been built to ease the traffic congestion in Mahipalpur. These roads join to NH-8 and Vasant Kunj marg near sector E traffic juncture.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Vasant Kunj Marg]]\n* [[Defence Colony]]\n* [[Greater Kailash]]\n* [[South West Delhi]] district\n* [[South Delhi]] district\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Neighborhoods of Delhi}}\n\n{{coord missing|Delhi}}\n\n[[Category:New Delhi]]\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Delhi]]\n[[Category:South West Delhi district]]\n", "name_user": "Gdrged", "label": "safe", "comment": "Mahipalpur interlinked", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vasant_Kunj"}
{"title_page": "Wolfgang Schleidt", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Cleanup reorganize|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n'''Wolfgang M. Schleidt''' (* December 18. 1927 in Vienna, Austria) is an Austrian Scientist in the area of [[bioacoustics]], communication and \u201eclassical ethology\u201c.<ref name=\"Sch\u00f6nberger2015\">Sch\u00f6nberger, A.: Wolfgang Schleidt \u2013 Der Tonmeister. In: Alwin Sch\u00f6nberger: Grenzg\u00e4nger. \u00d6sterreichische Pioniere zwischen Triumph und Tragik. Brandst\u00e4tter Verlag (2015), ISBN 978-3850338974; Sch\u00f6nberger, A., Horak P.: Portrait Wolfgang Schleidt, Pionier der Verhaltensforschung. Profil 49 (17), S. 70 - 73 (2018).</ref> He was assistant to Konrad Lorenz (1950 \u2013 65), professor of zoology, [[University of Maryland]] (1965\u201385) and director at the [[Konrad Lorenz Institut for Ethology]], Vienna of the Austrian Academy of Sciences. He was an early pioneer of Bioacoustics   and of the quantitative analysis of behaviour.<ref name=\"Schleidt1948\">Schleidt, W. M.: T\u00f6ne hoher Frequenz bei M\u00e4usen. Experientia: interdisciplinary journal for the life sciences 4 (4), S. 145 - 146 (1948), [[doi:10.1007/BF02164342]]</ref><ref name=\"Schleidt1952\">Schleidt, W. M.: Reaktionen auf T\u00f6ne hoher Frequenz bei Nagern. Die Naturwissenschaften 39 (3), S. 69 - 70 (1952) [[doi:10.1007/BF00596819]].</ref>\n \nWolfgang M. Schleidt grew up in Vienna, Austria and \u2013 age 17 \u2013 was drafted into the German Army in 1944, hat his left hand crippled in an encounter with a soviet tank and \u2013 while recuperating in the Army hospital in Memmingen \u2013 survive the air raid of the US Air Force with a permanent hearing loss of 60 DB at 4&nbsp;kHz. The crippled hand disqualified him for medical school (his preferred academic institution), and he decided to study biology and anthropology, with special emphasis on sensory and behavioral physiology.<ref name=\"Sch\u00f6nberger2015\" />\n\nHis hearing loss around 4&nbsp;kHz increased his awareness of vocalizations of mice in the range between 10 and 20&nbsp;kHz. At that time, the technology for electronic sound recording and loudspeakers was limited to the range between 100&nbsp;Hz and 8&nbsp;kHz and, in order to provide a convincing proof of the use of ultrasound, Schleidt started to develop and build his own electronic gadgets and thus became a pioneer of bioacoustics and animal communication.<ref name=\"Schleidt1948\" /><ref name=\"Schleidt1952\" /><ref>Zippelius, H. M.; Schleidt, W. M.: Ultraschall-Laute bei jungen M\u00e4usen. Die Naturwissenschaften 43, S. 502 - 502 (1956) [[doi:10.1007/BF00632534]].</ref><ref name=\"Schleidt1961\">Schleidt, W. M.: Reaktionen von Truth\u00fchnern auf fliegende Raubv\u00f6gel und Versuche zur Analyse ihrer AAM's. Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Tierpsychologie 18, S. 534 - 560 (1961) [[doi:10.1111/j.1439-0310.1961.tb00241.x]].</ref><ref name=\"Schleidt1974\">Schleidt, W. M.: How \"fixed\" is the fixed action pattern? Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Tierpsychologie 36, S. 184 - 211 (1974) [[doi:10.1111/j.1439-0310.1974.tb02131.x]].</ref>\n\n[[Konrad Lorenz]] became Schleidt's most influential teacher and when he became the Director of his own Forschungsstelle of the Max-Planck Gesellschaft in Buldern (Westphalia, Germany) he asked him to become his first Assistant. Wolfgang M. Schleidt served as the Supervisor of construction of the newly founded [[Max-Planck-Institut]] for Behavioral Physiology in Bavaria, Germany, suggested the Name \u201cSeewiesen\u201d for this location and became its first resident together with his wife Margret Schleidt, daughter Christiane and a flock of 400 wild geese. During his tenure at Seewiesen he started his critical review of basic concepts of Ethology.<ref name=\"Schleidt1961\" /><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Schleidt, M.; Magg, M.: St\u00f6rung der Mutterkind-Beziehung bei Truth\u00fchnern durch Geh\u00f6rverlust. Behaviour 16 (3-4), S. 254 - 260 (1960) [[doi: 10.1163/156853960X00179]]</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.: Tonic communication: Continual effects of discrete signs in animal communication systems. Journal of Theoretical Biology 42 (2), S. 359 - 386 (1973), [[doi:10.1016/0022-5193(73)90095-7]]</ref>\n\nAfter one year as visiting research professor at Duke University (1964\u201365) with Peter H. Klopfer and Donald K. Adams<ref name=\"duke\">https://scholars.duke.edu/person/phk; https://www.ncpedia.org/biography/adams-donald-keith</ref> Wolfgang M. Schleidt became professor of zoology at the University of Maryland (1965\u201385) and leader of the ethology group at the department of zoology, where he continued his research in quantitative ethology and animal communication.<ref name=\"Schleidt1974\" /><ref name=\"duke\" /><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Crawley, J. N.: Patterns in the behavior of organisms. Journal of Social and Biological Structures 3 (1), S. 1 - 15 (1980) [[doi:10.1016/0140-1750(80)90016-0]].</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.: Learning and the description of the environment. In: Issues in the ecological study of learning, S. 305 - 325 (Hg. Johnston, T. D.; Pietrewicz, A. T.). Lawrence Erlbaum Associates, Hillsdale, New Jersey (1985)</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Yakalis, G.; Donnelly, M.; McGarry, J.: A proposal for a standard ethogram, exemplified by an ethogram of the bluebreasted quail (Coturnix-chinensis). Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Tierpsychologie 64 (3-4), S. 193 - 220 (1984) [[doi:10.1111/j.1439-0310.1984.tb00360.x]]</ref> 1985 became Wolfgang M. Schleidt director at the Institute for comparative behavior research of the Austrian Academy of Sciences. He retired in 1992, but continued teaching at the University of Vienna till 2003, and is to this day working and publishing.<ref>Schleidt, W. M.: Epilog: Wer war der Vater der Graug\u00e4nse wirklich? In: Eigentlich wollte ich Wildgans werden. Aus meinem Leben, S. 97 - 122 (Hg. Lorenz, K.). Piper, M\u00fcnchen, Z\u00fcrich (2003), ISBN 978-3-492-04540-7</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Shalter, M. D.; Moura-Neto, H.: The hawk/goose story: The classical ethological experiments of Lorenz and Tinbergen, revisited. Journal of Comparative Psychology 125 (2), S. 121 - 133 (2011) [[doi:10.1037/a0022068]] and [[doi:10.1037/a0022068.supp]], [https://sites.ualberta.ca/~elegge/Alrg_Docs/Schleidt_2011.pdf (PDF)], </ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M. (2015): Lorenz, Konrad (1903\u201389). In: James D. Wright (editor-in-chief), International Encyclopedia of the Social & Behavioral Sciences, 2nd edition, Vol 14. 2015. Oxford: Elsevier. pp. 366\u2013371</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Shalter, M. D.: Dogs and mankind: Coevolution on the move - An update. Human Ethology Bulletin 33 (1), S. 15 - 38 (2018). Also hanging in the net as: http://ishe.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/HEB_2018_33_1_15-38.pdf</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:Duke University people]]\n[[Category:Austrian scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Cleanup reorganize|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n'''Wolfgang M. Schleidt''' (* December 18. 1927 in Vienna, Austria) is an Austrian Scientist in the area of [[bioacoustics]], communication and \u201eclassical ethology\u201c.<ref name=\"Sch\u00f6nberger2015\">Sch\u00f6nberger, A.: Wolfgang Schleidt \u2013 Der Tonmeister. In: Alwin Sch\u00f6nberger: Grenzg\u00e4nger. \u00d6sterreichische Pioniere zwischen Triumph und Tragik. Brandst\u00e4tter Verlag (2015), ISBN 978-3850338974; Sch\u00f6nberger, A., Horak P.: Portrait Wolfgang Schleidt, Pionier der Verhaltensforschung. Profil 49 (17), S. 70 - 73 (2018).</ref> He was assistant to Konrad Lorenz (1950 \u2013 65), professor of zoology, [[University of Maryland]] (1965\u201385) and director at the [[Konrad Lorenz Institut for Ethology]], Vienna of the Austrian Academy of Sciences. He was an early pioneer of Bioacoustics   and of the quantitative analysis of behaviour.<ref name=\"Schleidt1948\">Schleidt, W. M.: T\u00f6ne hoher Frequenz bei M\u00e4usen. Experientia: interdisciplinary journal for the life sciences 4 (4), S. 145 - 146 (1948), [[doi:10.1007/BF02164342]]</ref><ref name=\"Schleidt1952\">Schleidt, W. M.: Reaktionen auf T\u00f6ne hoher Frequenz bei Nagern. Die Naturwissenschaften 39 (3), S. 69 - 70 (1952) [[doi:10.1007/BF00596819]].</ref>\n \nWolfgang M. Schleidt grew up in Vienna, Austria and \u2013 age 17 \u2013 was drafted into the German Army in 1944, hat his left hand crippled in an encounter with a soviet tank and \u2013 while recuperating in the Army hospital in Memmingen \u2013 survive the air raid of the US Air Force with a permanent hearing loss of 60 DB at 4&nbsp;kHz. The crippled hand disqualified him for medical school (his preferred academic institution), and he decided to study biology and anthropology, with special emphasis on sensory and behavioral physiology.<ref name=\"Sch\u00f6nberger2015\" />\n\nHis hearing loss around 4&nbsp;kHz increased his awareness of vocalizations of mice in the range between 10 and 20&nbsp;kHz. At that time, the technology for electronic sound recording and loudspeakers was limited to the range between 100&nbsp;Hz and 8&nbsp;kHz and, in order to provide a convincing proof of the use of ultrasound, Schleidt started to develop and build his own electronic gadgets and thus became a pioneer of bioacoustics and animal communication.<ref name=\"Schleidt1948\" /><ref name=\"Schleidt1952\" /><ref>Zippelius, H. M.; Schleidt, W. M.: Ultraschall-Laute bei jungen M\u00e4usen. Die Naturwissenschaften 43, S. 502 - 502 (1956) [[doi:10.1007/BF00632534]].</ref><ref name=\"Schleidt1961\">Schleidt, W. M.: Reaktionen von Truth\u00fchnern auf fliegende Raubv\u00f6gel und Versuche zur Analyse ihrer AAM's. Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Tierpsychologie 18, S. 534 - 560 (1961) [[doi:10.1111/j.1439-0310.1961.tb00241.x]].</ref><ref name=\"Schleidt1974\">Schleidt, W. M.: How \"fixed\" is the fixed action pattern? Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Tierpsychologie 36, S. 184 - 211 (1974) [[doi:10.1111/j.1439-0310.1974.tb02131.x]].</ref>\n\n[[Konrad Lorenz]] became Schleidt's most influential teacher and when he became the Director of his own Forschungsstelle of the Max-Planck Gesellschaft in Buldern (Westphalia, Germany) he asked him to become his first Assistant. Wolfgang M. Schleidt served as the Supervisor of construction of the newly founded [[Max-Planck-Institut]] for Behavioral Physiology in Bavaria, Germany, suggested the Name \u201cSeewiesen\u201d for this location and became its first resident together with his wife Margret Schleidt, daughter Christiane and a flock of 400 wild geese. During his tenure at Seewiesen he started his critical review of basic concepts of Ethology.<ref name=\"Schleidt1961\" /><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Schleidt, M.; Magg, M.: St\u00f6rung der Mutterkind-Beziehung bei Truth\u00fchnern durch Geh\u00f6rverlust. Behaviour 16 (3-4), S. 254 - 260 (1960) [[doi: 10.1163/156853960X00179]]</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.: Tonic communication: Continual effects of discrete signs in animal communication systems. Journal of Theoretical Biology 42 (2), S. 359 - 386 (1973), [[doi:10.1016/0022-5193(73)90095-7]]</ref>\n\nAfter one year as visiting research professor at Duke University (1964\u201365) with Peter H. Klopfer and Donald K. Adams<ref name=\"duke\">https://scholars.duke.edu/person/phk; https://www.ncpedia.org/biography/adams-donald-keith</ref> Wolfgang M. Schleidt became professor of zoology at the University of Maryland (1965\u201385) and leader of the ethology group at the department of zoology, where he continued his research in quantitative ethology and animal communication.<ref name=\"Schleidt1974\" /><ref name=\"duke\" /><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Crawley, J. N.: Patterns in the behavior of organisms. Journal of Social and Biological Structures 3 (1), S. 1 - 15 (1980) [[doi:10.1016/0140-1750(80)90016-0]].</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.: Learning and the description of the environment. In: Issues in the ecological study of learning, S. 305 - 325 (Hg. Johnston, T. D.; Pietrewicz, A. T.). Lawrence Erlbaum Associates, Hillsdale, New Jersey (1985)</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Yakalis, G.; Donnelly, M.; McGarry, J.: A proposal for a standard ethogram, exemplified by an ethogram of the bluebreasted quail (Coturnix-chinensis). Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Tierpsychologie 64 (3-4), S. 193 - 220 (1984) [[doi:10.1111/j.1439-0310.1984.tb00360.x]]</ref> 1985 became Wolfgang M. Schleidt director at the Institute for comparative behavior research of the Austrian Academy of Sciences. He retired in 1992, but continued teaching at the University of Vienna till 2003, and is to this day working and publishing.<ref>Schleidt, W. M.: Epilog: Wer war der Vater der Graug\u00e4nse wirklich? In: Eigentlich wollte ich Wildgans werden. Aus meinem Leben, S. 97 - 122 (Hg. Lorenz, K.). Piper, M\u00fcnchen, Z\u00fcrich (2003), {{ISBN|978-3-492-04540-7}}</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Shalter, M. D.; Moura-Neto, H.: The hawk/goose story: The classical ethological experiments of Lorenz and Tinbergen, revisited. Journal of Comparative Psychology 125 (2), S. 121 - 133 (2011) [[doi:10.1037/a0022068]] and [[doi:10.1037/a0022068.supp]], [https://sites.ualberta.ca/~elegge/Alrg_Docs/Schleidt_2011.pdf (PDF)], </ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M. (2015): Lorenz, Konrad (1903\u201389). In: James D. Wright (editor-in-chief), International Encyclopedia of the Social & Behavioral Sciences, 2nd edition, Vol 14. 2015. Oxford: Elsevier. pp. 366\u2013371</ref><ref>Schleidt, W. M.; Shalter, M. D.: Dogs and mankind: Coevolution on the move - An update. Human Ethology Bulletin 33 (1), S. 15 - 38 (2018). Also hanging in the net as: http://ishe.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/HEB_2018_33_1_15-38.pdf</ref>\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:Duke University people]]\n[[Category:Austrian scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Schewinef\u00fc\u00dfe", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolfgang_Schleidt"}
{"title_page": "Regorafenib", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| drug_name         = \n| image             = Regorafenib.svg\n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n<!--Clinical data -->\n| tradename         = Stivarga, Regonix\n| Drugs.com         = {{drugs.com|monograph|regorafenib}}\n| MedlinePlus       = a613004\n| DailyMedID        = Regorafenib\n| pregnancy_AU      = D\n| pregnancy_US      = D\n| pregnancy_category= \n| licence_EU = yes\n| legal_AU = S4\n| legal_CA = Rx-only\n| legal_UK = POM\n| legal_US = Rx-only\n| legal_status      = \n| routes_of_administration = [[By mouth]]\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data -->\n| bioavailability   = 69-83%\n| protein_bound     = 99.5%\n| metabolism        = Hepatic ([[UGT1A9]]-mediated)\n| elimination_half-life = 20-30 hours\n| excretion         = Feces (71%), urine (19%)\n<!--Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number        = 755037-03-7\n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = 24T2A1DOYB\n| ATCvet            = \n| ATC_prefix        = L01\n| ATC_suffix        = XE21\n| PubChem           = 11167602\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 68647\n| DrugBank          = DB08896\n| ChemSpiderID = 9342697\n| KEGG              = D10138\n| ChEMBL            = 1946170\n| synonyms          = BAY 73-4506\n<!--Chemical data -->\n| IUPAC_name        = 4-[4-({[4-Chloro-3-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]carbamoyl}amino)-3-fluorophenoxy]-''N''-methylpyridine-2-carboxamide hydrate\n| C=21 | H=15 | Cl=1 | F=4 | N=4 | O=3\n| SMILES         = CNC(=O)c1cc(ccn1)Oc2ccc(c(c2)F)NC(=O)Nc3ccc(c(c3)C(F)(F)F)Cl\n| StdInChI = 1S/C21H15ClF4N4O3/c1-27-19(31)18-10-13(6-7-28-18)33-12-3-5-17(16(23)9-12)30-20(32)29-11-2-4-15(22)14(8-11)21(24,25)26/h2-10H,1H3,(H,27,31)(H2,29,30,32)\n| StdInChIKey = FNHKPVJBJVTLMP-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Regorafenib''', sold under the brand name '''Stivarga''' among others, is an oral multi-kinase inhibitor developed by [[Bayer]] which targets angiogenic, stromal and oncogenic [[receptor tyrosine kinase]] (RTK). Regorafenib shows anti-[[Angiogenesis|angiogenic]] activity due to its dual targeted [[VEGF receptors|VEGFR2-TIE2]] tyrosine kinase inhibition. Since 2009 it was studied as a potential treatment option in multiple tumor types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.bayer.com/baynews/baynews.nsf/id/291E08301C088221C1257634001EA3C7 |title=Bayer Announces New Data on Oncology Portfolio To Be Presented at the ECCO-ESMO Congress 2009 |format= |website= |access-date=2009-09-19}}</ref> By 2015 it had two US approvals for advanced cancers.\n\n==Approvals and indications==\n\n===Metastatic colorectal cancer===\nRegorafenib demonstrated to increase the overall survival of patients with metastatic [[colorectal cancer]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.press.bayer.com/baynews/baynews.nsf/id/Phase-III-Trial-Regorafenib-Metastatic-Colorectal-Cancer-Meets-Primary-Endpoint-Improving-Overall?Open&ccm=001|title=Phase III Trial of Regorafenib in Metastatic Colorectal Cancer Meets Primary Endpoint of Improving Overall Survival|access-date=2011-10-26|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119104218/http://www.press.bayer.com/baynews/baynews.nsf/id/Phase-III-Trial-Regorafenib-Metastatic-Colorectal-Cancer-Meets-Primary-Endpoint-Improving-Overall?Open&ccm=001|archive-date=2012-01-19}}</ref> and has been approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration|US FDA]] on September 27, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm321271.htm |title=FDA approves new treatment for advanced colorectal cancer |date=27 Sep 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter a manufacturer's appeal Regorafenib was restored to the list of treatments funded by the English [[Cancer Drugs Fund]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cancer fund reprieve for just one drug, Regorafenib|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-32835516|access-date=7 June 2015|publisher=BBC|date=22 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Advanced gastrointestinal stromal tumours===\nOn February 25, 2013 the US FDA expanded the approved use to treat patients with advanced [[gastrointestinal stromal tumor]]s that cannot be surgically removed and no longer respond to other FDA-approved treatments for this disease. In a clinical study with 199 patients regorafenib treated patients had a delay in tumor growth (progression-free survival) that was, on average, 3.9 months longer than patients who were given placebo.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm340958.htm |title=FDA approves Stivarga for advanced gastrointestinal stromal tumors |date=25 Feb 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Advanced hepatocellular carcinoma===\nOn November 29, 2018 the [[National Institute for Health and Care Excellence]] (NICE) approved use of regorafenib in patients with advanced [[hepatocellular carcinoma]] who were previously treated with [[sorafenib]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nice.org.uk/news/article/life-extending-treatment-for-patients-with-advanced-liver-cancer-recommended-by-nice|title=Life extending treatment for patients with advanced liver cancer recommended by NICE|date=November 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Clinical trials==\nMetastaticCRC: After the CORRECT trial, two phase 3 trials (CONSIGN, CONCUR) showed benefits compared to placebo. Regorafenib dosing was 150 or 160&nbsp;mg/d for first 3 weeks of each 4 week cycle.<ref name=CN2015>[http://www.cancernetwork.com/esmo-2015-world-gi/consign-concur-confirm-efficacy-regorafenib-mcrc CONSIGN, CONCUR Confirm Efficacy of Regorafenib in mCRC. 2015]</ref>\n\n==Adverse effects==\nRegorafenib is being approved with a Boxed Warning alerting patients and health care professionals that severe and fatal liver toxicity occurred in patients treated with regorafenib during clinical studies. Serious side effects, which occurred in less than one percent of patients, were liver damage, severe bleeding, blistering and peeling of skin, very high blood pressures requiring emergency treatment, heart attacks and perforations (holes) in the intestines. The most common side effects reported in patients treated with regorafenib include weakness or fatigue, loss of appetite, [[hand-foot syndrome]] (also called palmar-plantar erythrodysesthesia), diarrhoea, mouth sores (mucositis), weight loss, infection, high blood pressure, and changes in voice volume or quality ([[dysphonia]]).<ref>{{cite web | title=FDA Prescribing Information | url=http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2012/203085lbl.pdf |date=27 Sep 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Other actions==\nRegorafenib and at least one of its analogs, sorafenib, are potent inhibitors of [[Soluble epoxide hydrolase]] (sEH).<ref name=\"pmid24345640\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhang G, Kodani S, Hammock BD | title = Stabilized epoxygenated fatty acids regulate inflammation, pain, angiogenesis and cancer | journal = Progress in Lipid Research | volume = 53 | pages = 108\u201323 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24345640 | pmc = 3914417 | doi = 10.1016/j.plipres.2013.11.003 }}</ref>  sEH metabolizes, and in general thereby inactivates, [[epoxyeicosatrienoic acid]]s (EETs), [[epoxydocosapentaenoic acid]]s (EDPs), epoxyeicosatetraenoic acids (EEQs), and other epoxy polyunsaturated fatty acids that are made by various [[cytochrome P450]] [[epoxygenase]]s.  EETs, EDPs, and EEQs have various effects in animals including vasodilation, anti-hypertensive, and anti-blood-clotting actions.  However, EDPs, unlike EETs, inhibit the vascularization, growth, and metastasis of human cancer cells in vitro and in animal models.<ref name=\"pmid24345640\"/> It is suggested that the inhibition of sEH and consequential increase in EDP levels contributes to the anti-cancer activity of regorafenib and related analogs,<ref name=\"pmid24345640\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hwang SH, Wecksler AT, Zhang G, Morisseau C, Nguyen LV, Fu SH, Hammock BD | title = Synthesis and biological evaluation of sorafenib- and regorafenib-like sEH inhibitors | journal = Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry Letters | volume = 23 | issue = 13 | pages = 3732\u20137 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23726028 | pmc = 3744640 | doi = 10.1016/j.bmcl.2013.05.011 }}</ref> a possibility supported by studies showing that ''1)'' DHA acted synergistically with regorafenib to increase EDP levels in and inhibit the growth of several human renal cancer cell lines in vitro and ''2)'' dietary DHA likewise acted synergistically with regorafenib to inhibit the invasiveness and growth of a human renal cancer cell line while increasing its EPA levels in mice.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kim J, Ulu A, Wan D, Yang J, Hammock BD, Weiss RH | title = Addition of DHA Synergistically Enhances the Efficacy of Regorafenib for Kidney Cancer Therapy | journal = Molecular Cancer Therapeutics | volume = 15 | issue = 5 | pages = 890\u20138 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 26921392 | pmc = 4873345 | doi = 10.1158/1535-7163.MCT-15-0847 }}</ref>  These [[preclinical studies]] suggest that dietary supplementation with [[omega-3 fatty acids]], particularly DHA, may be useful in enhancing the anti-cancer actions of regorafenib in humans.\n\n==Brand names==\nIn [[Bangladesh]] under the trade name Regonix.{{mcn|date=March 2020}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | url = https://druginfo.nlm.nih.gov/drugportal/name/regorafenib | publisher = U.S. National Library of Medicine | work = Drug Information Portal | title = Regorafenib }}\n\n{{Extracellular chemotherapeutic agents}}\n{{Growth factor receptor modulators}}\n{{Portal bar | Pharmacy and pharmacology | Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Receptor tyrosine kinase inhibitors]]\n[[Category:Pyridines]]\n[[Category:Ureas]]\n[[Category:Bayer brands]]\n[[Category:Trifluoromethyl compounds]]\n[[Category:Chloroarenes]]\n[[Category:Fluoroarenes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| drug_name         = \n| image             = Regorafenib.svg\n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n<!--Clinical data -->\n| tradename         = Stivarga, Regonix\n| Drugs.com         = {{drugs.com|monograph|regorafenib}}\n| MedlinePlus       = a613004\n| DailyMedID        = Regorafenib\n| pregnancy_AU      = D\n| pregnancy_US      = D\n| pregnancy_category= \n| licence_EU = yes\n| legal_AU = S4\n| legal_CA = Rx-only\n| legal_UK = POM\n| legal_US = Rx-only\n| legal_status      = \n| routes_of_administration = [[By mouth]]\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data -->\n| bioavailability   = 69-83%\n| protein_bound     = 99.5%\n| metabolism        = Hepatic ([[UGT1A9]]-mediated)\n| elimination_half-life = 20-30 hours\n| excretion         = Feces (71%), urine (19%)\n<!--Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number        = 755037-03-7\n| ATCvet            = \n| ATC_prefix        = L01\n| ATC_suffix        = XE21\n| PubChem           = 11167602\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 68647\n| DrugBank          = DB08896\n| ChemSpiderID = 9342697\n| KEGG              = D10138\n| ChEMBL            = 1946170\n| synonyms          = BAY 73-4506\n<!--Chemical data -->\n| IUPAC_name        = 4-[4-({[4-Chloro-3-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]carbamoyl}amino)-3-fluorophenoxy]-''N''-methylpyridine-2-carboxamide hydrate\n| C=21 | H=15 | Cl=1 | F=4 | N=4 | O=3\n| SMILES         = CNC(=O)c1cc(ccn1)Oc2ccc(c(c2)F)NC(=O)Nc3ccc(c(c3)C(F)(F)F)Cl\n| StdInChI = 1S/C21H15ClF4N4O3/c1-27-19(31)18-10-13(6-7-28-18)33-12-3-5-17(16(23)9-12)30-20(32)29-11-2-4-15(22)14(8-11)21(24,25)26/h2-10H,1H3,(H,27,31)(H2,29,30,32)\n| StdInChIKey = FNHKPVJBJVTLMP-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Regorafenib''', sold under the brand name '''Stivarga''' among others, is an oral multi-kinase inhibitor developed by [[Bayer]] which targets angiogenic, stromal and oncogenic [[receptor tyrosine kinase]] (RTK). Regorafenib shows anti-[[Angiogenesis|angiogenic]] activity due to its dual targeted [[VEGF receptors|VEGFR2-TIE2]] tyrosine kinase inhibition. Since 2009 it was studied as a potential treatment option in multiple tumor types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.bayer.com/baynews/baynews.nsf/id/291E08301C088221C1257634001EA3C7 |title=Bayer Announces New Data on Oncology Portfolio To Be Presented at the ECCO-ESMO Congress 2009 |format= |website= |access-date=2009-09-19}}</ref> By 2015 it had two US approvals for advanced cancers.\n\n==Approvals and indications==\n\n===Metastatic colorectal cancer===\nRegorafenib demonstrated to increase the overall survival of patients with metastatic [[colorectal cancer]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.press.bayer.com/baynews/baynews.nsf/id/Phase-III-Trial-Regorafenib-Metastatic-Colorectal-Cancer-Meets-Primary-Endpoint-Improving-Overall?Open&ccm=001|title=Phase III Trial of Regorafenib in Metastatic Colorectal Cancer Meets Primary Endpoint of Improving Overall Survival|access-date=2011-10-26|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119104218/http://www.press.bayer.com/baynews/baynews.nsf/id/Phase-III-Trial-Regorafenib-Metastatic-Colorectal-Cancer-Meets-Primary-Endpoint-Improving-Overall?Open&ccm=001|archive-date=2012-01-19}}</ref> and has been approved by the [[Food and Drug Administration|US FDA]] on September 27, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm321271.htm |title=FDA approves new treatment for advanced colorectal cancer |date=27 Sep 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter a manufacturer's appeal Regorafenib was restored to the list of treatments funded by the English [[Cancer Drugs Fund]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cancer fund reprieve for just one drug, Regorafenib|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-32835516|access-date=7 June 2015|publisher=BBC|date=22 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Advanced gastrointestinal stromal tumours===\nOn February 25, 2013 the US FDA expanded the approved use to treat patients with advanced [[gastrointestinal stromal tumor]]s that cannot be surgically removed and no longer respond to other FDA-approved treatments for this disease. In a clinical study with 199 patients regorafenib treated patients had a delay in tumor growth (progression-free survival) that was, on average, 3.9 months longer than patients who were given placebo.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm340958.htm |title=FDA approves Stivarga for advanced gastrointestinal stromal tumors |date=25 Feb 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Advanced hepatocellular carcinoma===\nOn November 29, 2018 the [[National Institute for Health and Care Excellence]] (NICE) approved use of regorafenib in patients with advanced [[hepatocellular carcinoma]] who were previously treated with [[sorafenib]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nice.org.uk/news/article/life-extending-treatment-for-patients-with-advanced-liver-cancer-recommended-by-nice|title=Life extending treatment for patients with advanced liver cancer recommended by NICE|date=November 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Clinical trials==\nMetastaticCRC: After the CORRECT trial, two phase 3 trials (CONSIGN, CONCUR) showed benefits compared to placebo. Regorafenib dosing was 150 or 160&nbsp;mg/d for first 3 weeks of each 4 week cycle.<ref name=CN2015>[http://www.cancernetwork.com/esmo-2015-world-gi/consign-concur-confirm-efficacy-regorafenib-mcrc CONSIGN, CONCUR Confirm Efficacy of Regorafenib in mCRC. 2015]</ref>\n\n==Adverse effects==\nRegorafenib is being approved with a Boxed Warning alerting patients and health care professionals that severe and fatal liver toxicity occurred in patients treated with regorafenib during clinical studies. Serious side effects, which occurred in less than one percent of patients, were liver damage, severe bleeding, blistering and peeling of skin, very high blood pressures requiring emergency treatment, heart attacks and perforations (holes) in the intestines. The most common side effects reported in patients treated with regorafenib include weakness or fatigue, loss of appetite, [[hand-foot syndrome]] (also called palmar-plantar erythrodysesthesia), diarrhoea, mouth sores (mucositis), weight loss, infection, high blood pressure, and changes in voice volume or quality ([[dysphonia]]).<ref>{{cite web | title=FDA Prescribing Information | url=http://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2012/203085lbl.pdf |date=27 Sep 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Other actions==\nRegorafenib and at least one of its analogs, sorafenib, are potent inhibitors of [[Soluble epoxide hydrolase]] (sEH).<ref name=\"pmid24345640\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhang G, Kodani S, Hammock BD | title = Stabilized epoxygenated fatty acids regulate inflammation, pain, angiogenesis and cancer | journal = Progress in Lipid Research | volume = 53 | pages = 108\u201323 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24345640 | pmc = 3914417 | doi = 10.1016/j.plipres.2013.11.003 }}</ref>  sEH metabolizes, and in general thereby inactivates, [[epoxyeicosatrienoic acid]]s (EETs), [[epoxydocosapentaenoic acid]]s (EDPs), epoxyeicosatetraenoic acids (EEQs), and other epoxy polyunsaturated fatty acids that are made by various [[cytochrome P450]] [[epoxygenase]]s.  EETs, EDPs, and EEQs have various effects in animals including vasodilation, anti-hypertensive, and anti-blood-clotting actions.  However, EDPs, unlike EETs, inhibit the vascularization, growth, and metastasis of human cancer cells in vitro and in animal models.<ref name=\"pmid24345640\"/> It is suggested that the inhibition of sEH and consequential increase in EDP levels contributes to the anti-cancer activity of regorafenib and related analogs,<ref name=\"pmid24345640\"/><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hwang SH, Wecksler AT, Zhang G, Morisseau C, Nguyen LV, Fu SH, Hammock BD | title = Synthesis and biological evaluation of sorafenib- and regorafenib-like sEH inhibitors | journal = Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry Letters | volume = 23 | issue = 13 | pages = 3732\u20137 | date = July 2013 | pmid = 23726028 | pmc = 3744640 | doi = 10.1016/j.bmcl.2013.05.011 }}</ref> a possibility supported by studies showing that ''1)'' DHA acted synergistically with regorafenib to increase EDP levels in and inhibit the growth of several human renal cancer cell lines in vitro and ''2)'' dietary DHA likewise acted synergistically with regorafenib to inhibit the invasiveness and growth of a human renal cancer cell line while increasing its EPA levels in mice.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kim J, Ulu A, Wan D, Yang J, Hammock BD, Weiss RH | title = Addition of DHA Synergistically Enhances the Efficacy of Regorafenib for Kidney Cancer Therapy | journal = Molecular Cancer Therapeutics | volume = 15 | issue = 5 | pages = 890\u20138 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 26921392 | pmc = 4873345 | doi = 10.1158/1535-7163.MCT-15-0847 }}</ref>  These [[preclinical studies]] suggest that dietary supplementation with [[omega-3 fatty acids]], particularly DHA, may be useful in enhancing the anti-cancer actions of regorafenib in humans.\n\n==Brand names==\nIn [[Bangladesh]] under the trade name Regonix.{{mcn|date=March 2020}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web | url = https://druginfo.nlm.nih.gov/drugportal/name/regorafenib | publisher = U.S. National Library of Medicine | work = Drug Information Portal | title = Regorafenib }}\n\n{{Extracellular chemotherapeutic agents}}\n{{Growth factor receptor modulators}}\n{{Portal bar | Pharmacy and pharmacology | Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Receptor tyrosine kinase inhibitors]]\n[[Category:Pyridines]]\n[[Category:Ureas]]\n[[Category:Bayer brands]]\n[[Category:Trifluoromethyl compounds]]\n[[Category:Chloroarenes]]\n[[Category:Fluoroarenes]]\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regorafenib"}
